<ProjectLayout title="Overview" activeSlug="overview">
  <h2>Project Abstract</h2>
  <p>
    This project takes in sound inputs — from a keyboard, any instrument, or singing — transcribes the sound
    onto a score in real-time at a given BPM, and plays back the input melody. An FPGA is used as the main
    calculation and display engine, using Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) for frequency analysis and driving a
    VGA display. An MCU interfaces the audio inputs.
  </p>
  <p>
    An analog microphone takes in sounds; the MCU converts them to digital signals using ADC and sends
    them to the FPGA over SPI. The FPGA uses FFT to extract the frequency and duration of each note.
    The array of notes is used by the FPGA to calculate pixel positions and display a score on a VGA monitor.
  </p>

  <h2>Project Motivation</h2>
  <p>
    Both of us are interested in digital design and audio processing, and wanted to leverage the FPGA's fast
    computational capabilities to process sound. Due to the importance and wide applications of FFT, we
    wanted to design and integrate FFT in hardware. We chose VGA to display the output because accurately
    depicting a music score requires high pixel resolution.
  </p>

